SIMPLE: memory
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Memory
<hw>Mem"o*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Memories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>memorie</ets>,
OF. <ets>memoire</ets>, <ets>memorie</ets>, F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧moire</ets>, L. <ets>memoria</ets>, fr. <ets>memor</ets>
mindful; cf. <ets>mora</ets> delay. Cf. <er>Demur</er>, <er>Martyr</er>,
<er>Memoir</er>, <er>Remember</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The faculty of the mind by which it retains the
knowledge of previous thoughts, impressions, or events.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Memory</qex> is the purveyor of reason.</q>
<rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The reach and positiveness with which a person can
remember; the strength and trustworthiness of one's power to reach and
represent or to recall the past; <as>as, his <ex>memory</ex> was never
wrong</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The actual and distinct retention and recognition of
past ideas in the mind; remembrance; <as>as, in <ex>memory</ex> of
youth; <ex>memories</ex> of foreign lands.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The time within which past events can be or are
remembered; <as>as, within the <ex>memory</ex> of man</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And what, before thy <qex>memory</qex>, was done⟦br⟧
From the begining.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Something, or an aggregate of things, remembered;
hence, character, conduct, etc., as preserved in remembrance, history,
or tradition; posthumous fame; <as>as, the war became only a
<ex>memory</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>memory</qex> of the just is blessed.</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
x. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That ever-living man of <qex>memory</qex>, Henry the Fifth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Nonconformists . . . have, as a body, always venerated her
[Elizabeth's] <qex>memory</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A memorial.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These weeds are <qex>memories</qex> of those worser hours.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Memory</er>, <er>Remembrance</er>,
<er>Recollection</er>, <er>Reminiscence</er>.</syn> <usage>
<xex>Memory</xex> is the generic term, denoting the power by which we
reproduce past impressions. <xex>Remembrance</xex> is an exercise of
that power when things occur <xex>spontaneously</xex> to our thoughts.
In <xex>recollection</xex> we make a distinct effort to <xex>collect
again</xex>, or call back, what we know has been formerly in the mind.
<xex>Reminiscence</xex> is intermediate between <xex>remembrance</xex>
and <xex>recollection</xex>, being a conscious process of recalling past
occurrences, but without that full and varied reference to particular
things which characterizes <xex>recollection</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧When an idea
again recurs without the operation of the like object on the external
sensory, it is <xex>remembrance</xex>; if it be sought after by the
mind, and with pain and endeavor found, and brought again into view, it
is <xex>recollection</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj> </usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To draw to memory</b></col>, <cd>to put on record; to
record. </cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.
Gower.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memphian</ent>⟦br⟧
